    p1Challenge: "Plant data was scattered across sites and systems, with no consistent, trustworthy foundation for cross-plant analytics or decisions.",
    p1Approach: "I helped design a centralized Data Layer on Databricks following the medallion architecture (Bronze → Silver → Gold), turning heterogeneous plant signals into curated, analytics-ready data.",
    p1Architecture: "A lakehouse with progressive refinement: raw ingestion (Bronze), cleaned and conformed data (Silver), and dimensional, business-facing marts (Gold) — unified across continents.",
    p1Decisions: "Delta Lake for ACID reliability and time travel; dimensional modeling at the Gold layer; a layered design that isolates raw capture from business semantics so each can evolve independently.",
    p1Implementation: "End-to-end ETL pipelines ingesting diverse plant sources, with conformed dimensions and curated marts feeding analytics across multiple industrial sites.",
    p1Outcome: "A single, trusted data foundation that made cross-plant analytics possible and replaced fragmented, ad-hoc data flows.",
    p1Lessons: "Investing early in layer separation and modeling discipline kept the platform scalable as new plants and sources were onboarded.",
    p2Challenge: "Leadership lacked a unified, reliable view of operational and strategic performance across the organization.",
    p2Approach: "I helped define the KPIs that best reflect operational and strategic performance and built a unified dashboard on top of the curated Data Layer.",
    p2Architecture: "A consumption layer over the Gold marts, with a data-observability architecture monitoring the quality and freshness of the underlying data.",
    p2Decisions: "Anchoring data-quality metrics to ISO/IEC 25012 dimensions; automated alerting and monitoring dashboards so trust in the numbers is continuously verified, not assumed.",
    p2Implementation: "KPI definitions, dashboard development, and an observability layer with automated email alerts and quality dashboards across the Data Layer.",
    p2Outcome: "A trusted, unified KPI view — and an observability approach adopted as a standard across multiple projects and clients.",
    p2Lessons: "A dashboard is only as credible as the data beneath it; observability is what turns a report into a decision-making tool.",
    p3Challenge: "Meeting a target quality specification at minimum raw-material cost is a hard trade-off that was being solved manually and inconsistently.",
    p3Approach: "I contributed to an optimization engine that recommends the raw-material blend reaching the target quality at the lowest possible cost.",
    p3Architecture: "An optimization model balancing quality constraints against material cost, integrated into the plant's operational workflow.",
    p3Decisions: "Framing the problem as constrained optimization over the cost–quality frontier, so recommendations are explainable and tied to explicit business constraints.",
    p3Implementation: "Deployed for a specific plant, recommending blends that satisfy quality targets while minimizing cost.",
    p3Outcome: "Consistent, cost-aware blend recommendations replacing manual trial-and-error.",
    p3Lessons: "Framing an operational decision as an explicit optimization problem makes the trade-offs visible and the recommendations trustworthy.",
    p4Challenge: "Incoming scrap had to be identified, classified and routed quickly and accurately — a slow, error-prone manual step at the plant entrance.",
    p4Approach: "I contributed to an end-to-end system where an overhead camera reads the open-bed truck, classifies scrap type and quantity, directs the driver to the correct unloading bay, and syncs with inventory.",
    p4Architecture: "Computer-vision inference at the unloading area feeding a decisioning layer (bay routing) and an integration layer (inventory systems), with the observability architecture reused on top.",
    p4Decisions: "Reusing the proven observability architecture from earlier projects rather than rebuilding it; integrating classification directly into the physical unloading and inventory workflow.",
    p4Implementation: "Overhead-camera classification, real-time driver guidance, and automatic inventory integration, delivered for a plant in Argentina.",
    p4Outcome: "Meaningful operational gains; the observability layer was delivered as an extra and is already being replicated on other projects.",
    p4Lessons: "Reusable architecture compounds — solving observability once let us deliver it as added value across very different problems.",
    p5Challenge: "A multinational client needed a digital representation of its largest plant to anticipate behavior and support better operational decisions.",
    p5Approach: "I contributed to a digital twin including regression and classification models, a recommendation AI agent, and the backend and frontend the client interacts with.",
    p5Architecture: "ML models and an AI agent (Amazon Bedrock) behind a full-stack application, with AI-agent observability on AWS (Amazon CloudWatch and AWS X-Ray).",
    p5Decisions: "Structuring observability for the AI agent on AWS — metrics, logs and distributed tracing — so agent behavior is transparent and debuggable in production.",
    p5Implementation: "Predictive models, an AI recommendation agent, full-stack delivery, and an AWS-based observability layer for the agent.",
    p5Outcome: "An approach highly valued by the client and becoming their standard for industrial AI-agent observability.",
    p5Lessons: "As AI agents move into operations, observability is no longer optional — it is what makes them safe to rely on.",
    mBronzeT: "Bronze — Raw ingest",
